From: Finchley@aol.com
& Dr._Michael_Benenson_at_WRAIR15__WASHDC@wrsmtp-ccmail.army.mil
Date: Sat, 28 Aug 1999 22:51:23 EDT
Source: Reuters 28 Aug, 1999
Three Royal Bengal tigers, an endangered species, have died from an unknown
disease at Dhaka zoo (Bangladesh) in the past 3 days, zoo officials said on
Saturday. An investigation had been ordered after the third tiger died early
on Saturday, they said.
"We are not yet certain about the cause of their deaths. But we suspect the
deaths have been caused by a disease called trypanosomiasis, a protozoan
disease of African origin. The disease could spread through mosquito or fly
bites,'' Dr. Nazrul Islam, chief veterinary physician at the zoo told
Reuters.
"I believe all the tigers who belonged to the same family and lived in the
same cage were attacked by bot fly. No other tiger of the zoo is affected by
the disease.''
Two Bengal tigers were killed by food poisoning at the zoo last year.
Apart from 15 tigers remaining at the zoo, Bangladesh has some 400 Bengal
tigers left in the coastal Sundarban forest, nearly 400 km (250 miles) south
of Dhaka, according to official estimates.
